commons_description:
{'DateTime': {'value': '2024-02-18 08:33:30', 'source': 'mediawiki-metadata', 'hidden': ''}, 'ObjectName': {'value': 'SDO 20150505 000217 4096 1600 (AIA)', 'source': 'mediawiki-metadata'}, 'CommonsMetadataExtension': {'value': 1.2, 'source': 'extension', 'hidden': ''}, 'Categories': {'value': '2015 AIA photos of the Sun|AIA photos of the Sun at 1600 Å|Files from NASA with known IDs|PD NASA|Photographs taken on 2015-05-05|Spacemedia files uploaded by OptimusPrimeBot', 'source': 'commons-categories', 'hidden': ''}, 'Assessments': {'value': '', 'source': 'commons-categories', 'hidden': ''}, 'ImageDescription': {'value': 'AIA 1600 channel (as well as AIA 1700) often shows a web-like pattern of bright areas that highlight places where bundles of magnetic fields lines are concentrated. However, small areas with a lot of field lines will appear black, usually near sunspots and active regions.

Where: Transition region and upper photosphere

X-axis data interval is monthly. Y-axis concentration is parts per trillion.

Atmospheric samples were gathered within evacuated flasks from 8-12 ground stations distributed over the northern (positive latitudes) and southern hemispheres, then sealed and transported to Boulder Colorado for analysis. Most emissions originate at northern latitudes, and are mixed through the troposphere of both hemispheres after about 1-2 years.

{'DateTime': {'value': '2024-03-17 00:24:52', 'source': 'mediawiki-metadata', 'hidden': ''}, 'ObjectName': {'value': 'SDO 20131118 000000 4096 HMIBC (HMI)', 'source': 'mediawiki-metadata'}, 'CommonsMetadataExtension': {'value': 1.2, 'source': 'extension', 'hidden': ''}, 'Categories': {'value': '2013 HMI images of the Sun|Colorized magnetograms by HMI|Files from NASA with known IDs|Files with no machine-readable source|Images without source|PD NASA|Spacemedia files uploaded by OptimusPrimeBot', 'source': 'commons-categories', 'hidden': ''}, 'Assessments': {'value': '', 'source': 'commons-categories', 'hidden': ''}, 'ImageDescription': {'value': "HMI measures the Sun's magnetic field over the entire visible disk with 1 arc second resolution. The line of sight magnetic field color table is designed to visually show structure at both high and low field values.

Field strengths <24 G are shades of gray. Positive Field Values are green and blue. Negative field values are yellow and red.

Weak field regions appear mostly yellow or green. Increasingly positive values range from dark green to bright green at 236G. Negative values move from bright yellow to orange at -236G.

There is a sharp discontinuity in color at 236G.

Positive or negative polarity sunspots and other strong field regions will appear blue or red with dark umbrae.

There are 254 defined colors symmetrically arranged around the zero point.

The 127 positive include 2 darkening gray, 18 brightening green, and 110 darkening blue.

The 127 negative include 2 brightening gray, 18 darkening yellow, and 107 darkening red.

Nominally, each color spans a range of ~11.81 G and the color table extends from -1500 to 1500 G.", 'source': 'commons-desc-page'}, 'Artist': {'value': 'Courtesy of NASA/SDO and the AIA, EVE, and HMI science teams.', 'source': 'commons-desc-page'}, 'LicenseShortName': {'value': 'Public domain', 'source': 'commons-desc-page', 'hidden': ''}, 'UsageTerms': {'value': 'Public domain', 'source': 'commons-desc-page'}, 'AttributionRequired': {'value': 'false', 'source': 'commons-desc-page', 'hidden': ''}, 'Copyrighted': {'value': 'False', 'source': 'commons-desc-page', 'hidden': ''}, 'Restrictions': {'value': '', 'source': 'commons-desc-page', 'hidden': ''}, 'License': {'value': 'pd', 'source': 'commons-templates', 'hidden': ''}}
